   =20
 =20
A rough, inaccurate but useful way to think about U.S. equity market struct=
ure is that the prices on the stock exchange are bad. You can go to a publi=
c stock exchange and see a =E2=80=9Clit,=E2=80=9D public bid and offer for =
every stock; the exchange will tell you at all times, like, =E2=80=9Cyou ca=
n buy this stock for $10.05 or sell it for $9.95.=E2=80=9D (The best buying=
 and selling price available on all the lit exchanges=C2=A0is called the =
=E2=80=9Cnational best bid and offer=E2=80=9D or NBBO.)=C2=A0But if you eve=
r find yourself paying the lit price to buy a stock, or accepting the lit p=
rice to sell it, you have done poorly. That is just the sticker price, the =
advertised price, the price for rubes.=C2=A0Somewhere, in the dark, there a=
re hidden orders at better prices, and=C2=A0if you and your broker are any =
good you will find them.=C2=A0I want to stress that this is rough and inacc=
urate; if you work for a stock exchange, or for an electronic market maker =
that quotes on the exchanges, you don=E2=80=99t have to email me to be like=
 =E2=80=9Cactually our quotes are great.=E2=80=9D I just mean that, to unde=
rstand what people get=C2=A0mad about in market structure, it is often help=
ful to start from the premise =E2=80=9Cthey think the=C2=A0NBBO is bad.=E2=
=80=9DIf you start from that premise you can build a model in which there a=
re basically four different =E2=80=9Cmarket=E2=80=9D prices for a stock. In=
 ascending order:=09The national best bid is the price you=E2=80=99d get if=
 you tried to sell the stock on a lit stock exchange. This price is too low=
. Say it=E2=80=99s $9.95.=09The =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D best bid is the best=
 price you could find to sell the stock if you knew where to look. Say ther=
e=E2=80=99s some dark pool somewhere where someone has a hidden order to bu=
y the stock at $9.99; if you find that order you can sell at $9.99.=09The =
=E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D best offer is the best price you could find to buy t=
he stock if you knew where to look. Say it=E2=80=99s $10.01.=09The national=
 best offer is the best price you could find to buy the stock on a lit stoc=
k exchange. This price is too high. Say it=E2=80=99s $10.05.Prices 1 and 4,=
 the NBBO, are transparent; anyone can see what they are. Prices 2 and 3, t=
he =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D best prices available in dark pools and hidden li=
quidity and internalizers=E2=80=99 books and so forth, are not; certain sor=
ts of experts know what they are but most people have to guess at them.Your=
 goal, as a person looking to buy or sell stock, is to find the real=C2=A0b=
est price, by scouring dark pools and knowing a lot about markets and routi=
ng orders cleverly, or by having a trusted intermediary do that for you. Th=
e goal of the expert intermediary selling you the stock is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0w=
ell, their goal is complicated. Their goal is to (1) make money for themsel=
ves and (2) keep you coming back.If they sell you stock at=C2=A0worse=C2=A0=
prices than the NBBO they will get in trouble. If they sell you stock at th=
e NBBO, they will do well =E2=80=94 on this model,=C2=A0they=C2=A0can buy s=
tock at the real best price and resell it to you at the NBBO, keeping the d=
ifference for themselves =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if you are sophisticated you wo=
n=E2=80=99t keep coming back. This model is so widely understood that execu=
ting trades at the NBBO=C2=A0is often considered bad. What you want is to g=
et =E2=80=9Cprice improvement,=E2=80=9D to execute at some price better tha=
n the NBBO, so that you think you=C2=A0might=C2=A0be getting the real price=
.=C2=A0And so the game for the expert intermediaries selling you the stock =
is to sell it to you at some price between the lit best price and the real =
best price. You try to buy stock, the national best offer is $10.05, your b=
roker says =E2=80=9Cgood news, we got you price improvement, you=E2=80=99re=
 filled at $10.03.=E2=80=9D You are happy because you got a better price th=
an the NBBO; you got the great-customer discount; you might even have gotte=
n the real price, what do you know. The market maker who sold you the stock=
 is happy because it can buy at $10.01 (the real best price) and sell at $1=
0.03 (the price-improved, better-than-NBBO-but-still-worse-than-real best p=
rice). If you knew that the real price was $10.01 you=E2=80=99d be mad, but=
 you don=E2=80=99t; for all you know the real price was $10.03, you got it,=
 and you=E2=80=99re doing great.This model is too cynical, but I think it a=
ccurately captures why people are mad about payment for order flow for reta=
il stock trading. We have  discussed payment for order flow=C2=A0several ti=
mes before, in more sensible and less cynical ways, but on the cynical mode=
l all PFOF is is:=09You send an order to your broker.=09Your broker sends i=
t to a wholesaler, an electronic market maker for retail customers.=09The w=
holesaler buys it at the real price, say $10.01.=09The wholesaler sells it =
to you at some price-improved price, say $10.03.=09The wholesaler makes $0.=
02.=09The wholesaler gives some of that money to your broker as payment for=
 getting to do this free-money trade.Again, again, too cynical. The wronges=
t part of this model is probably point 3; the wholesaler does=C2=A0not, as =
a general matter, go out and =E2=80=9Cfront-run=E2=80=9D your order by buyi=
ng it at the real price and turning around to sell it to you at a higher pr=
ice. (The wholesaler runs a book, trades with you out of inventory,=C2=A0ha=
s its own model of the correct price, tries to trade at some spread around =
that, etc.) But people do get really mad about payment for order flow,=C2=
=A0even though it gives retail customers better prices than they would get =
on the public stock exchange, and it is worth understanding that position. =
If you start from =E2=80=9Cwell, of course, but the prices on the public st=
ock exchange are for rubes, nobody pays those,=E2=80=9D it becomes pretty u=
nderstandable.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t really want to endorse the model I laid=
 out above except, oh man, look at this Securities and Exchange Commission =
enforcement action from Monday:The Securities and Exchange Commission insti=
tuted settled charges against Illinois-based Coda Markets, Inc. for making =
material omissions and misleading statements to the broker-dealer subscribe=
rs of its alternative trading system (ATS) about how it handled and routed =
orders for execution. =E2=80=A6The SEC's order finds that from December 201=
6 to July 2019, Coda failed to disclose its use of a circular routing arran=
gement when handling subscriber orders. According to the SEC's order, Coda =
disclosed that it created individually customized routing tables for the su=
bscribers to its ATS, with venues ranked in the routing tables depending on=
 the subscriber's trading priorities. The order finds that when Coda had di=
scretion over the routing table, Coda inserted one of two broker-dealers as=
 the first external destination because, among other reasons, Coda had agre=
ements with these broker-dealers to share the net trading profits on execut=
ions of orders routed from Coda.=C2=A0Coda is a broker-dealer, and it runs =
a dark pool called Coda ATS. Some of its customers were subscribers to its =
dark pool; they would send orders to Coda, and Coda would either execute th=
e orders in the dark pool or, for =E2=80=9Cthe vast majority of Coda=E2=80=
=99s order flow,=E2=80=9D route them somewhere else: It would send an order=
 to other dark pools and stock exchanges until it executed, with the dark p=
ools and exchanges ranked on some criteria along the lines of =E2=80=9Cwher=
e will we get the best price.=E2=80=9D Customers would send their orders to=
 Coda because they hoped to buy stock at the real price, rather than the li=
t price. Maybe the stock is for sale at the real price in Coda=E2=80=99s da=
rk pool, and they=E2=80=99ll buy it there, or maybe it=E2=80=99s for sale a=
t the real price in some other dark pool, and Coda, which is smart, will ro=
ute their orders to that pool so they can buy it there.=C2=A0And then here=
=E2=80=99s what Coda did:During the relevant period, Coda had agreements wi=
th two other broker-dealers to execute orders received from Coda by trading=
 on a net basis (the =E2=80=9CNet Trading Firms=E2=80=9D), wherein Coda pre=
scribed how the Net Trading Firms would handle the majority of the orders t=
hey received from Coda.=C2=A0When Coda routed a subscriber order to one of =
the Net Trading Firms, the Net Trading Firm would hold the subscriber order=
 in reserve and then, in most cases, send a principal order back to Coda. C=
oda would then route the Net Trading Firm=E2=80=99s principal order to one =
or more external markets to seek non-displayed liquidity. If the Net Tradin=
g Firm=E2=80=99s principal order executed, Coda would communicate the execu=
tion(s) back to the Net Trading Firm, which would then effect an offsetting=
 trade with the subscriber at a net price which was different than the pric=
e of the trade obtained by Coda on the external market for the principal or=
der.The Net Trading Firms and Coda agreed that they would price the offsett=
ing leg (between the Net Trading Firm and the subscriber) such that the Net=
 Trading Firm would provide 5% of the price improvement to Coda=E2=80=99s s=
ubscriber order, and retain the remaining 95% of the price improvement.Duri=
ng the relevant period, Coda had a profit sharing agreement with the Net Tr=
ading Firms. When a Net Trading Firm executed an order routed from Coda, th=
e Net Trading Firm paid Coda approximately 70% of the net trading profit de=
rived from the net trade.=C2=A0That is:=09Coda would get a customer order t=
o buy stock.=09Coda would send that order to one of its partner firms (the =
=E2=80=9CNet Trading Firms=E2=80=9D) to execute.=09They would say =E2=80=9C=
hang on a minute.=E2=80=9D=09They would send=C2=A0their=C2=A0order to buy t=
he same stock back to the Coda dark pool.=09Coda would send=C2=A0that=C2=A0=
order to some other dark pools to try to buy stock at the real price (=E2=
=80=9Cto one or more external markets to seek non-displayed liquidity=E2=80=
=9D).=09Coda would come back to the partner firm and say =E2=80=9Cgood news=
, you bought the stock at $10.01.=E2=80=9D=09The partner firm would say =E2=
=80=9Cgreat, also, we sold the stock to your customer at $10.048.=E2=80=9D[=
1]=09Coda would go back to the customer and say =E2=80=9Cgood news, your or=
der got filled in our dark pool at $10.048, which is $0.002 better than the=
 national best offer of $10.05 on the lit stock exchange.=E2=80=9D=09The pa=
rtner firm would say to Coda =E2=80=9Cpleasure doing business with you, her=
e=E2=80=99s $0.027.=E2=80=9D[2]The customers think they have=C2=A0no cause =
for complaint, because they did better than the NBBO. The whole thing is an=
 institutional equivalent of retail payment for order flow: The partner fir=
ms fill the customers at a better price than the NBBO, make some profit for=
 themselves, and kick back some of it to the broker (Coda).[3]It seems =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0quite =E2=80=A6=C2=A0bad? Like the customers went to Coda expec=
ting it to just=C2=A0route their order where it would get the best price. (=
Because Coda sort of said that that=E2=80=99s what it would do.) Instead it=
 gave the order to its partner net trading firms, then sent=C2=A0their=C2=
=A0orders where they would get the best price, then let them fill the custo=
mers=E2=80=99=C2=A0orders at a worse price, and then took a kickback. It is=
 probably not technically =E2=80=9Cfront-running,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0but it is s=
ort of front-running-adjacent. The customers got no value for it; the SEC s=
ays:Coda was not =E2=80=9Cseeking liquidity=E2=80=9D from the Net Trading F=
irms because the Net Trading Firms usually took no steps to obtain liquidit=
y for the subscriber order, and pursuant to the arrangement with Coda, usua=
lly would route a principal order directly back to Coda so that Coda could =
route it to an away market for execution.It could have just done that with =
the customer order, instead of going through the net trading firms. But the=
n it wouldn=E2=80=99t get its money.Anyway Coda and its president settled w=
ith the SEC for about $1.2 million in fines, without admitting or denying t=
he findings. Also this all ended long ago:By December 2019, Coda stopped th=
e circular routing arrangement described above. Coda also ended its profit =
sharing agreements with the Net Trading Firms. Since December 2019, Coda ha=
s had an agreement with a market maker to pay Coda fixed payments for order=
 flow as agreed by the parties.=C2=A0Ah, well, I=E2=80=99m sure that=E2=80=
=99s fine then.
