<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><table class=3D"header" =
width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bad PFOF</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A rough, inaccurate but useful way to =
think about U.S. equity market structure is that the prices on the stock ex=
change are bad. You can go to a public stock exchange and see a =E2=80=9Cli=
t,=E2=80=9D public bid and offer for every stock; the exchange will tell yo=
u at all times, like, =E2=80=9Cyou can buy this stock for $10.05 or sell it=
 for $9.95.=E2=80=9D (The best buying and selling price available on all th=
e lit exchanges=C2=A0is called the =E2=80=9Cnational best bid and offer=E2=
=80=9D or NBBO.)=C2=A0But if you ever find yourself paying the lit price to=
 buy a stock, or accepting the lit price to sell it, you have done poorly. =
That is just the sticker price, the advertised price, the price for rubes.=
=C2=A0<em>Somewhere</em>, in the dark, there are hidden orders at better pr=
ices, and=C2=A0if you and your broker are any good you will find them.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to stress that this is rough and=
 inaccurate; if you work for a stock exchange, or for an electronic market =
maker that quotes on the exchanges, you don=E2=80=99t have to email me to b=
e like =E2=80=9Cactually our quotes are great.=E2=80=9D I just mean that, t=
o understand what people get=C2=A0<em>mad </em>about in market structure, i=
t is often helpful to start from the premise =E2=80=9Cthey think the=C2=A0N=
BBO is bad.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you start from that=
 premise you can build a model in which there are basically four different =
=E2=80=9Cmarket=E2=80=9D prices for a stock. In ascending order:</p><ol sty=
le=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The national best bid is the price you=E2=80=
=99d get if you tried to sell the stock on a lit stock exchange. This price=
 is too low. Say it=E2=80=99s $9.95.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">The =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D best bid is the best price you could find to =
sell the stock if you knew where to look. Say there=E2=80=99s some dark poo=
l somewhere where someone has a hidden order to buy the stock at $9.99; if =
you find that order you can sell at $9.99.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">The =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D best offer is the best price you could =
find to buy the stock if you knew where to look. Say it=E2=80=99s $10.01.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The national best offer is the best=
 price you could find to buy the stock on a lit stock exchange. This price =
is too high. Say it=E2=80=99s $10.05.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Prices 1 and 4, the NBBO, are transparent; anyone can see what they are. P=
rices 2 and 3, the =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D best prices available in dark poo=
ls and hidden liquidity and internalizers=E2=80=99 books and so forth, are =
not; certain sorts of experts know what they are but most people have to gu=
ess at them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Your goal, as a person looking=
 to buy or sell stock, is to find the real=C2=A0best price, by scouring dar=
k pools and knowing a lot about markets and routing orders cleverly, or by =
having a trusted intermediary do that for you. The goal of the expert inter=
mediary selling you the stock is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, their goal is complic=
ated. Their goal is to (1) make money for themselves and (2) keep you comin=
g back.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If they sell you stock at=C2=A0<em>=
worse=C2=A0</em>prices than the NBBO they will get in trouble. If they sell=
 you stock at the NBBO, they will do well =E2=80=94 on this model,=C2=A0<em=
>they=C2=A0</em>can buy stock at the real best price and resell it to you a=
t the NBBO, keeping the difference for themselves =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if you=
 are sophisticated you won=E2=80=99t keep coming back. This model is so wid=
ely understood that executing trades at the NBBO=C2=A0is often considered b=
ad. What you want is to get =E2=80=9Cprice improvement,=E2=80=9D to execute=
 at some price better than the NBBO, so that you think you=C2=A0<em>might=
=C2=A0</em>be getting the real price.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>And so the game for the expert intermediaries selling you the stock is to =
sell it to you at some price between the lit best price and the real best p=
rice. You try to buy stock, the national best offer is $10.05, your broker =
says =E2=80=9Cgood news, we got you price improvement, you=E2=80=99re fille=
d at $10.03.=E2=80=9D You are happy because you got a better price than the=
 NBBO; you got the great-customer discount; you might even have gotten the =
real price, what do you know. The market maker who sold you the stock is ha=
ppy because it can buy at $10.01 (the real best price) and sell at $10.03 (=
the price-improved, better-than-NBBO-but-still-worse-than-real best price).=
 If you knew that the real price was $10.01 you=E2=80=99d be mad, but you d=
on=E2=80=99t; for all you know the real price was $10.03, you got it, and y=
ou=E2=80=99re doing great.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This model is to=
o cynical, but I think it accurately captures why people are mad about paym=
ent for order flow for retail stock trading. We have <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25123929.273053/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDUvcm9iaW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXN=
hZ2EtcHJlc3N1cmVzLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3c/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3=
c1484f4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> =
discussed</a> payment for order flow=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/25123929.273053/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDgtMzEvd2hhdC1oYXBwZW5zLXRvLXJvYmluaG9vZC1pZi=
10aGUtc2VjLWJhbnMtcGF5bWVudC1mb3Itb3JkZXItZmxvdy1rdDBhNWtqZw/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBc15b4571" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">several times</a> before, in more sensible and less cynical wa=
ys, but on the cynical model all PFOF is is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-typ=
e: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">You send an order to your broker.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">Your broker sends it to a wholesaler, an electronic market maker=
 for retail customers.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The wholesa=
ler buys it at the real price, say $10.01.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">The wholesaler sells it to you at some price-improved price, say $=
10.03.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The wholesaler makes $0.02.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The wholesaler gives some of that=
 money to your broker as payment for getting to do this free-money trade.</=
li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, again, too cynical. The wronges=
t part of this model is probably point 3; the wholesaler does=C2=A0<em>not<=
/em>, as a general matter, go out and =E2=80=9Cfront-run=E2=80=9D your orde=
r by buying it at the real price and turning around to sell it to you at a =
higher price. (The wholesaler runs a book, trades with you out of inventory=
,=C2=A0has its own model of the correct price, tries to trade at some sprea=
d around that, etc.) But people do get really mad about payment for order f=
low,=C2=A0<em>even though it gives retail customers better prices than they=
 would get on the public stock exchange</em>, and it is worth understanding=
 that position. If you start from =E2=80=9Cwell, of course, but the prices =
on the public stock exchange are for rubes, nobody pays those,=E2=80=9D it =
becomes pretty understandable.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=
=E2=80=99t really want to endorse the model I laid out above except, oh man=
, look at this Securities and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25123929.273053/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
lbmZvcmNlLzMzLTEwOTg1LXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBad44e3ca" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">enforcement action from M=
onday</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and E=
xchange Commission instituted settled charges against Illinois-based Coda M=
arkets, Inc. for making material omissions and misleading statements to the=
 broker-dealer subscribers of its alternative trading system (ATS) about ho=
w it handled and routed orders for execution. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">The SEC's order finds that from December 2016 to July 2019, Co=
da failed to disclose its use of a circular routing arrangement when handli=
ng subscriber orders. According to the SEC's order, Coda disclosed that it =
created individually customized routing tables for the subscribers to its A=
TS, with venues ranked in the routing tables depending on the subscriber's =
trading priorities. The order finds that when Coda had discretion over the =
routing table, Coda inserted one of two broker-dealers as the first externa=
l destination because, among other reasons, Coda had agreements with these =
broker-dealers to share the net trading profits on executions of orders rou=
ted from Coda.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Coda is a=
 broker-dealer, and it runs a dark pool called Coda ATS. Some of its custom=
ers were subscribers to its dark pool; they would send orders to Coda, and =
Coda would either execute the orders in the dark pool or, for =E2=80=9Cthe =
vast majority of Coda=E2=80=99s order flow,=E2=80=9D route them somewhere e=
lse: It would send an order to other dark pools and stock exchanges until i=
t executed, with the dark pools and exchanges ranked on some criteria along=
 the lines of =E2=80=9Cwhere will we get the best price.=E2=80=9D Customers=
 would send their orders to Coda because they hoped to buy stock at the rea=
l price, rather than the lit price. Maybe the stock is for sale at the real=
 price in Coda=E2=80=99s dark pool, and they=E2=80=99ll buy it there, or ma=
ybe it=E2=80=99s for sale at the real price in some other dark pool, and Co=
da, which is smart, will route their orders to that pool so they can buy it=
 there.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then here=E2=80=99s <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25123929.273053/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjEvMzMtMTA5ODUucGRm/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB2a9b33b8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">what Coda did</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">During the relevant period, Coda had agreements with two other broker-d=
ealers to execute orders received from Coda by trading on a net basis (the =
=E2=80=9CNet Trading Firms=E2=80=9D), wherein Coda prescribed how the Net T=
rading Firms would handle the majority of the orders they received from Cod=
a.=C2=A0When Coda routed a subscriber order to one of the Net Trading Firms=
, the Net Trading Firm would hold the subscriber order in reserve and then,=
 in most cases, send a principal order back to Coda. Coda would then route =
the Net Trading Firm=E2=80=99s principal order to one or more external mark=
ets to seek non-displayed liquidity. If the Net Trading Firm=E2=80=99s prin=
cipal order executed, Coda would communicate the execution(s) back to the N=
et Trading Firm, which would then effect an offsetting trade with the subsc=
riber at a net price which was different than the price of the trade obtain=
ed by Coda on the external market for the principal order.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">The Net Trading Firms and Coda agreed that they would price=
 the offsetting leg (between the Net Trading Firm and the subscriber) such =
that the Net Trading Firm would provide 5% of the price improvement to Coda=
=E2=80=99s subscriber order, and retain the remaining 95% of the price impr=
ovement.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the relevant period, Coda h=
ad a profit sharing agreement with the Net Trading Firms. When a Net Tradin=
g Firm executed an order routed from Coda, the Net Trading Firm paid Coda a=
pproximately 70% of the net trading profit derived from the net trade.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is:</p><ol style=3D"l=
ist-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Coda would get a customer order to buy stock.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Coda would send that order to one of i=
ts partner firms (the =E2=80=9CNet Trading Firms=E2=80=9D) to execute.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They would say =E2=80=9Chang on a minu=
te.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They would send=C2=A0=
<em>their=C2=A0</em>order to buy the same stock back to the Coda dark pool.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Coda would send=C2=A0<em>that=C2=
=A0</em>order to some other dark pools to try to buy stock at the real pric=
e (=E2=80=9Cto one or more external markets to seek non-displayed liquidity=
=E2=80=9D).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Coda would come back t=
o the partner firm and say =E2=80=9Cgood news, you bought the stock at $10.=
01.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The partner firm woul=
d say =E2=80=9Cgreat, also, we sold the stock to your customer at $10.048.=
=E2=80=9D[1]</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Coda would go back to=
 the customer and say =E2=80=9Cgood news, your order got filled in our dark=
 pool at $10.048, which is $0.002 better than the national best offer of $1=
0.05 on the lit stock exchange.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">The partner firm would say to Coda =E2=80=9Cpleasure doing business =
with you, here=E2=80=99s $0.027.=E2=80=9D[2]</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The customers think they have=C2=A0no cause for complaint, because =
they did better than the NBBO. The whole thing is an institutional equivale=
nt of retail payment for order flow: The partner firms fill the customers a=
t a better price than the NBBO, make some profit for themselves, and kick b=
ack some of it to the broker (Coda).[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It =
seems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0quite =E2=80=A6=C2=A0bad? Like the customers went to C=
oda expecting it to just=C2=A0<em>route their order where it would get the =
best price</em>. (Because Coda sort of said that that=E2=80=99s what it wou=
ld do.) Instead it gave the order to its partner net trading firms, then se=
nt=C2=A0<em>their=C2=A0</em>orders where they would get the best price, the=
n let them fill the customers=E2=80=99=C2=A0orders at a worse price, and th=
en took a kickback. It is probably not technically =E2=80=9Cfront-running,=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0but it is sort of front-running-adjacent. The customers got =
no value for it; the SEC says:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Coda was not =E2=80=9Cseeking liquidity=E2=80=9D from the Net Trading Firms=
 because the Net Trading Firms usually took no steps to obtain liquidity fo=
r the subscriber order, and pursuant to the arrangement with Coda, usually =
would route a principal order directly back to Coda so that Coda could rout=
e it to an away market for execution.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">It could have just done that with the customer order, instead of go=
ing through the net trading firms. But then it wouldn=E2=80=99t get its mon=
ey.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Coda and its president settled w=
ith the SEC for about $1.2 million in fines, without admitting or denying t=
he findings. Also this all ended long ago:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">By December 2019, Coda stopped the circular routing arrangement=
 described above. Coda also ended its profit sharing agreements with the Ne=
t Trading Firms. Since December 2019, Coda has had an agreement with a mark=
et maker to pay Coda fixed payments for order flow as agreed by the parties=
.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ah, well, I=E2=80=99m =
