</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I used to work in an equity capital ma=
rkets group at an investment bank so <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/25123929.273053/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9u=
ZXctcGxhdGZvcm0tYmFja2VkLWJ5LWZpZGVsaXR5LWdvbGRtYW4tc2Vla3MtdG8tYnJpbmctaXB=
vLW1hcmtldC1pbnRvLWRpZ2l0YWwtd29ybGQtMTE2MzIzODk0MDE_bW9kPWhwX2xpc3RhX3Bvcz=
E/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdfaabfab" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">this brought back happy memories</a>:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The syndicate desk=E2=80=94a longtime fix=
ture at banks across Wall Street where IPOs and other large stock sales are=
 priced and allocated to investors=E2=80=94has long clung to traditional wa=
ys of doing business like phone orders and scribbled pieces of paper, even =
as other businesses go digital. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ben Bat=
ory, head of Franklin Equity Group Trading at Franklin Templeton, said for =
decades he and his team have kept track of how many shares they asked for i=
n IPOs=E2=80=94as well as how many they received and at what price=E2=80=94=
on loose sheets of paper. He and his counterparts at other firms talk of ca=
lling multiple bankers on a deal to make sure their orders are recorded cor=
rectly. And then they wait. The morning after an IPO prices, a banker calls=
 them, tells them how many shares they got, at what price, and what percent=
age of fees they owe to each of the dozen or so underwriters. It is up to M=
r. Batory, or someone in his shoes, to keep track of it all.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAll these things are ripe for error,=E2=80=9D he=
 said. =E2=80=9CThere can be five deals a day, and you need to get the amou=
nt right, get the commission right, and it=E2=80=99s all chicken scratch on=
 a piece of paper on my desk. It=E2=80=99s incredibly challenging.=E2=80=9D=
</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Would you believe that the so=
lution is to have some sort of website where customers can type in how many=
 shares they want, and then the banks could look at the order book and deci=
de how many shares to allocate to each investor, and then the investors cou=
ld just see on the website how many shares they got and how much they had t=
o pay? Seems too easy, doesn't it? Like if it were as simple as that someon=
e would have just done it, right? Ha well anyway:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Capital Markets Gateway LLC has set out to change that=
. Backed by Franklin Templeton, Fidelity Investments, Goldman Sachs Group I=
nc., JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. and Morgan Stanley,=C2=A0among others, CMG wa=
s launched in 2017 by former bankers at Robert W. Baird &amp; Co. =E2=80=A6=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When the system is up and running, buy-sid=
e firms=E2=80=94of which nearly 100 are signed up=E2=80=94will be able to s=
ee what deals are pricing when, what the terms are and digitally enter thei=
r orders with lead bankers, so long as they have an existing relationship w=
ith them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Once IPOs and other offerings are=
 priced, instead of waiting until the following morning to learn via a phon=
e call if they received any allocation, fund managers can find out electron=
ically that same evening.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Isn=E2=80=99t technology amazing. My <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/25123929.273053/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZX=
dzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjAtMDgtMDMvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtbm93LWFuLWFwcC1jYW4tcGl0Y=
2gtbWVyZ2Vycw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBce1c57f0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">basic theory</a> is that there are a=
 lot of areas of finance where much of the lucrative value-add that a highl=
y paid expert provides is, like, =E2=80=9Cremembering who wants to buy a st=
ock=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cremembering the terms of the last 10 deals=E2=80=
=9D or whatever. Much of the work that investment banks do requires nuanced=
 judgment and creativity and boldness and deep personal connections; some o=
f it =E2=80=A6=C2=A0does not.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If people cal=
l you up and say =E2=80=9CI want to buy the stock=E2=80=9D and you write do=
wn their names on a piece of paper and put it in your pocket, you can go to=
 the client and say =E2=80=9CI have a $10 billion book of demand for your s=
tock,=E2=80=9D and the client will be like =E2=80=9Cwow you are amazing, ou=
r hero, here=E2=80=99s a $20 million fee to pay for your expertise and hard=
 work and market knowledge and investor relationships.=E2=80=9D Whereas if =
people type their orders on a website and the client looks at the website a=
nd sees $10 billion of demand for the stock and you are standing next to th=
e website looking important the client will say =E2=80=9Ccould you move ple=
ase, you=E2=80=99re blocking our view of the website.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just putting all this stuff on a computer demystifies =
it a bit, which is probably not great for margins. Or maybe it=E2=80=99s gr=
eat for margins insofar as it allows the bank to replace highly paid high-t=
ouch professionals with scalable apps; it=E2=80=99s just not great for bank=
er compensation. And my other basic theory is that the goal of an investmen=
t=C2=A0bank is to maximize banker compensation.=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"li=
