om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Meme stocks</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A key explanation of, like, modern lif=
e is that politics are so vicious and polarized because (1) everyone uses F=
acebook, (2) Facebook has an algorithm to decide what stuff to show people,=
 (3) that algorithm is built to maximize engagement, (4) the algorithm is v=
ery effective, and (5) it turns out that what maximizes engagement is vicio=
us polarizing stuff, oops. That probably exaggerates the role of Facebook=
=E2=80=99s algorithm and understates the agency of its users =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9CEverything you hate about the Internet is actually everything y=
ou hate about people,=E2=80=9D says <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/25123929.273053/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXdsLmNvbS8yMDE2LzExL=
3RoZS1zcGlyaXQtb2YtdGhlLWludGVybmV0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa0d81a44" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Balk=E2=80=99s=
 First Law</a> =E2=80=94 but there=E2=80=99s something to it. Social media =
reflects and also shapes human behavior, in an emergent=C2=A0way. It target=
s a behavior it likes =E2=80=94=C2=A0spending more time on Facebook, basica=
lly =E2=80=94 and tries to maximize it. To do that, it maximizes behaviors =
that correlate with the target behavior, like posting and reading vicious p=
olitical content. It gives people what they want, as revealed by their acti=
ons, which is not what they actually want. (Or is it?) And so at some level=
 you have behaviors in the real world that seem to be designed by an algori=
thm to maximize engagement on social media; politics are vicious and volati=
le because that=E2=80=99s what Facebook, deep down, wants.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Okay now let=E2=80=99s do stocks! At Margins, Ranjan Roy ha=
s a great post on =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/25123929.273053/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmVhZG1hcmdpbnMuY29tL3AvbWVtZXN0b2=
Nrcy1hbmQtcmVkZGl0LXJlZGVzaWducz90b2tlbj1leUoxYzJWeVgybGtJam94TURZM01Dd2ljR=
zl6ZEY5cFpDSTZOREUxTmpFMk1EZ3NJbDhpT2lJeFNub3pVU0lzSW1saGRDSTZNVFl6TWpJMk5q=
azROeXdpWlhod0lqb3hOak15TWpjd05UZzNMQ0pwYzNNaU9pSndkV0l0TmpZNE15SXNJbk4xWWl=
JNkluQnZjM1F0Y21WaFkzUnBiMjRpZlEuY19TWFRuN2l3V1Z2WFBfdnQyUVpQUEJ4SjZQR0tScV=
htS21NSWFqcHNqTQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB809a4bb5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Memestocks and Reddit redesigns</=
a>=E2=80=9D arguing that some of the 2021 meme-stock craze is due to change=
s in Reddit=E2=80=99s algorithms to maximize engagement: The stock market i=
s volatile and bizarre because that=E2=80=99s what Reddit, deep down, wants=
.=C2=A0You read about a stock, Reddit sends you =E2=80=9Cyou might also lik=
e ...=E2=80=9D notifications about that stock and other stocks, those notif=
ications are designed to draw you in, they work, you spend more time lookin=
g at stocks on Reddit, your identity starts to become =E2=80=9Cperson who c=
ares about this stock,=E2=80=9D you buy the stock, you start posting about =
it, you start buying weekly-expiry out-of-the-money call options on the sto=
ck and posting your daily profits and losses, the stock goes to $1,000, it =
becomes the biggest story in the national news, everyone in the country is =
obsessed with it, and=C2=A0<em>they are all coming to Reddit</em>=C2=A0beca=
use the story is not =E2=80=9Cstock goes up=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Cstock goe=
s up because people are having fun and getting rich on Reddit.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the dumb perspective of the Reddit=
 algorithm that sends you those notifications, this is what success looks l=
ike: It sent you those notifications, and now everyone is on Reddit. It is =
a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25123929.273053/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGVzc3dyb25nLmNvbS90YWcvcGFwZXJjbGlwLW1heGltaXplcg/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB59041733" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">paperclip maximizer</a>: Its goal is to get more people to=
 spend more time on Reddit, and the way it does that is to cause global fin=
ancial markets to be wildly volatile and disconnected from fundamental valu=
e because it turns out =E2=80=94=C2=A0who knew? =E2=80=94 that that drives =
more engagement with Reddit. Nobody at Reddit sat down and said =E2=80=9Che=
y we should pump up some weird stocks, that will maximize traffic=E2=80=9D;=
 its engagement algorithms just figured that out on their own. And now here=
 we are. Roy:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When the history =
of the memestock craze is written, there are a lot of known factors (or at =
least, they=E2=80=99re clear to me). ZIRP. Robinhood and the gamification o=
f trading. Stimulus checks and people sitting at home. But especially, in l=
ight of this week=E2=80=99s amazing Wall Street Journal series the Facebook=
 Files ...=C2=A0unanticipated consequences of engagement-driven algorithms =
are top of mind.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When Reddit raised a ton o=
f money and hired a media growth legend, I=E2=80=99m sure sending AMC to th=
e moon was never on anyone=E2=80=99s mind. But as we slowly try to make sen=
se of what=E2=80=99s happened in the financial markets over the past year, =
it=E2=80=99s worth remembering how a redirection in a business model and UX=
 tweaks can create massive outsized behavioral changes that make the world =
a lot weirder and harder to understand.</p></blockquote><table class=3D"hea=
der" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Evergrande</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess that if you are a financial re=
gulator there is something to be said for taking an inscrutable tough-love =
approach with companies that run into trouble:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;"><strong>Company:</strong> We are almost out of money and ha=
ve so many creditors. Should we prioritize delivering product to customers,=
 or paying suppliers, or making payments on debt to local retail investors,=
 or making payments on debt to offshore bond investors?</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;"><strong>Regulator:</strong> Yes.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;"><strong>Company:</strong> ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Re=
gulator:</strong> ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Company:</str=
ong> Okay, good one, ha ha ha,=C2=A0but seriously we can=E2=80=99t pay ever=
yone.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Regulator: </strong>Try.</p><=
/blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is the benefit, to the regula=
tor, of saying =E2=80=9Cif I were you I=E2=80=99d pay the retail investors =
and stiff the offshore ones=E2=80=9D? Why would you want to sound like you =
